{
  "idea": {
    "Name": "quantization_aware_gradient_flow",
    "Title": "Gradient Flow-Informed Bit-Width Allocation for Efficient Mixed Precision Quantization",
    "Short Hypothesis": "Integrating gradient flow sensitivity metrics into mixed precision quantization can enhance quantization efficiency and model performance without requiring retraining.",
    "Related Work": "Current mixed precision quantization techniques primarily focus on layer sensitivity or salience without considering the impact of gradient flow on quantization decisions. Our approach combines insights from gradient flow analysis with existing training-free methods to provide a more holistic view of layer importance, distinguishing it from methods like SliM-LLM and EMQ that do not incorporate this aspect.",
    "Abstract": "In the pursuit of optimizing mixed precision quantization (MPQ) for deep neural networks, the role of gradient flow has been largely overlooked. This work proposes a novel framework that leverages gradient flow sensitivity as a key metric in determining bit-width allocations for quantization. By assessing how gradients propagate through the network, we can identify layers where precision loss would have the least impact on overall performance. Our approach not only aims to maintain model accuracy but also enhances computational efficiency by minimizing quantization errors. We will empirically validate our method by conducting experiments on various neural architectures, comparing our framework's performance against existing state-of-the-art training-free quantization techniques. We anticipate that our method will yield a superior trade-off between accuracy and efficiency, thus contributing significantly to the field of model compression.",
    "Experiments": "1. Conduct experiments on standard datasets (e.g., ImageNet) using various architectures (e.g., ResNet, LSTM). 2. Implement a baseline MPQ method for comparison. 3. Develop a gradient flow analysis tool to quantify the impact of gradient propagation on each layer's bit-width allocation. 4. Evaluate the accuracy and computational efficiency of our method against baseline approaches using metrics such as model accuracy, inference speed, and memory consumption.",
