{
  "idea": {
    "Name": "inter-layer_dependency_aware_mixed_precision_quantization",
    "Title": "Inter-Layer Dependency Aware Mixed Precision Quantization: A Training-Free Approach",
    "Short Hypothesis": "Leveraging inter-layer dependencies in deep neural networks can significantly improve the effectiveness of mixed precision quantization while being training-free, providing a more stable and efficient quantization process.",
    "Related Work": "While several recent works have proposed training-free mixed-precision quantization techniques, such as InfoQ and EMQ, they either focus on local properties or require significant computational resources for optimization. This proposal distinguishes itself by emphasizing a systematic understanding of inter-layer dependencies, which has been less explored in the context of training-free quantization methods.",
    "Abstract": "Mixed Precision Quantization (MPQ) has become a cornerstone approach for optimizing deep neural networks, enhancing efficiency without significantly sacrificing performance. However, existing approaches often neglect the inter-layer dependencies that influence quantization sensitivity, resulting in suboptimal configurations. This paper proposes a novel training-free framework that systematically addresses these inter-layer dependencies by quantifying the impact of quantization on information flow across layers. By employing a forward-pass-based assessment method to derive global sensitivity scores, we formulate the bit-width allocation as an integer linear programming (ILP) problem. Our approach not only maintains high accuracy but also significantly reduces computational overhead compared to existing methods. We conduct extensive experiments across various architectures, demonstrating that our method achieves superior performance in terms of accuracy and efficiency, establishing a new standard for training-free mixed-precision quantization.",
    "Experiments": [
      "1. Implement a forward-pass sensitivity analysis to quantify inter-layer dependencies in selected neural network architectures (e.g., ResNet and MobileNet).",
      "2. Formulate the bit-width allocation problem as an integer linear programming (ILP) task based on derived sensitivity scores.",
      "3. Compare the proposed framework against state-of-the-art training-free quantization methods, measuring accuracy, computational efficiency, and memory footprint.",
      "4. Perform ablation studies to isolate the impact of inter-layer dependency awareness on quantization performance."
    ],
    "Risk Factors and Limitations": [
