Given the insights gathered from the literature search, we can propose a novel research idea that aligns with the methodological preferences outlined. The proposed idea aims to build upon the existing foundation of mixed-precision quantization while addressing gaps in understanding the relationship between quantization proxies and their performance outcomes.

### Refined Research Proposal

IDEA JSON:
```json
{
  "idea": {
    "Name": "adaptive_quantization_proxies",
    "Title": "Adaptive Quantization Proxies: Uncovering the Correlation Between Structural Features and Quantization Efficacy",
    "Short Hypothesis": "Can we systematically derive adaptive quantization proxies that leverage the intrinsic structural features of neural network architectures to enhance mixed-precision quantization outcomes?",
    "Related Work": "While existing works like EMQ and SNIP focus on optimizing quantization strategies, they often lack a clear understanding of the correlation between quantization proxies and model performance. This proposal aims to quantitatively analyze structural features and develop adaptive proxies based on their relationships to quantization efficacy, distinguishing it from prior research by emphasizing empirical correlation rather than heuristic or expert-driven quantization designs.",
    "Abstract": "Mixed-Precision Quantization (MPQ) has emerged as a critical technique for optimizing the performance of neural networks, particularly in resource-constrained environments. Despite advancements, the correlation between quantization proxies and their resultant accuracy remains insufficiently explored. This research proposes a novel framework for deriving Adaptive Quantization Proxies (AQP) that capitalize on structural features of neural networks to predict the efficacy of mixed-precision quantization. By leveraging curvature-aware geometric diagnostics, we aim to create a systematic approach to identify optimal bit-width configurations for different layers based on their intrinsic properties. Our framework will be empirically validated through a series of experiments on standard benchmarks, demonstrating improved accuracy and efficiency over existing quantization methods. This work promises to deepen our understanding of the structural underpinnings of quantization performance and establish a new direction for training-free quantization strategies.",
    "Experiments": [
      "Identify and characterize intrinsic structural features of various neural network architectures using curvature diagnostics.",
      "Develop an adaptive algorithm to correlate these features with quantization performance through a systematic search approach.",
      "Evaluate the proposed AQP framework against existing mixed-precision methods on benchmark datasets like ImageNet and COCO, measuring accuracy, computational efficiency, and memory savings.",
      "Use metrics such as layer-wise accuracy retention, computational overhead, and quantization error to validate the efficacy of adaptive proxies."
    ],
    "Risk Factors and Limitations": "Potential limitations include the challenge of accurately characterizing structural features across diverse architectures, the risk of overfitting the proxy model to specific datasets, and the computational overhead associated with the empirical validation of multiple architectures."
  }
}
```

### Evaluation of the Proposal

