    "Related Work": "Existing methods for mixed-precision quantization, such as EMQ and InfoQ, rely heavily on empirical evaluations or local sensitivity metrics. These approaches fail to leverage the intrinsic spectral properties of network weights, which could provide a more deterministic route to quantization without the need for extensive empirical tuning.",
    "Abstract": "In this proposal, we introduce a novel framework for mixed-precision quantization that leverages spectral properties of model weights to discover optimal quantization proxies in a training-free manner. Unlike conventional methods that depend on heuristic-based sensitivity metrics or empirical training, our framework employs spectral decomposition to identify key weight characteristics that govern model performance during quantization. We develop a spectral proxy discovery algorithm that computes the importance of each weight based on its eigenvalue distribution and exploits this information to allocate bit-widths dynamically across layers. This approach not only enhances the accuracy of quantized models but also simplifies the quantization process by reducing reliance on extensive search mechanisms. Experiments will validate the proposed framework across various architectures and datasets, demonstrating improved performance against state-of-the-art methods while adhering to stringent computational constraints.",
