    "Name": "adaptive_kv_quantization",
    "Title": "Dynamic Adaptive Quantization for Key-Value Caches in Large Language Models",
    "Short Hypothesis": "Leveraging context-sensitive characteristics of inputs to dynamically adjust quantization precision for key-value caches can significantly enhance inference efficiency and reduce latency in large language models without sacrificing accuracy.",
    "Related Work": "While existing works like KVTuner and Cocktail focus on static or semi-static approaches to quantization, often overlooking dynamic input characteristics, this proposal aims to introduce a fully dynamic context-sensitive quantization framework that adaptively adjusts based on real-time input analysis, distinguishing from existing literature by providing a more granular and responsive approach.",
    "Abstract": "Large language models (LLMs) have demonstrated remarkable capabilities but often struggle with inference latency, particularly in long-context scenarios. Recent advancements in mixed-precision quantization for key-value (KV) caches have sought to balance efficiency and performance, yet they frequently rely on static configurations that do not fully exploit the dynamic nature of input data. This paper proposes a novel dynamic adaptive quantization framework that leverages the context-sensitive characteristics of inputs to optimize quantization precision for KV caches in real-time. Our method will use a lightweight runtime analysis to assess contextual features, enabling the model to select optimal precision levels dynamically, thereby minimizing latency while maintaining accuracy. We will evaluate our approach against state-of-the-art static methods across various LLMs and tasks, demonstrating substantial improvements in inference throughput and reduced latency. This work aims to provide a foundation for future explorations into adaptive quantization techniques that can be applied more broadly across diverse model architectures.",
    "Experiments": [
      "Implement the dynamic adaptive quantization framework in existing LLM architectures.",
      "Conduct experiments comparing the new method against static KV quantization approaches (e.g., KVTuner, Cocktail) across various datasets and model sizes.",
      "Utilize metrics such as inference latency, accuracy, and throughput to evaluate performance.",
      "Perform ablation studies to understand the impact of different contextual features on quantization decisions."
    ],
    "Risk Factors and Limitations": "The primary risks involve the potential overhead from real-time analysis which may counteract benefits in certain scenarios. The framework's performance may vary significantly with different model architectures and tasks. Additionally, the reliance on context-sensitive features means that the model may need extensive training on diverse inputs to generalize effectively."
  }
}
