    "Related Work": "Existing studies have explored layer skipping strategies primarily in static settings or without rigorous performance constraints. This proposal distinguishes itself by employing real-time Jacobian-based assessments to dynamically decide layer execution during inference, thereby integrating latency considerations into the foundational structure of neural network architectures.",
    "Abstract": "In the landscape of machine learning inference, latency is a critical constraint for real-time applications. This proposal investigates an innovative approach to neural network inference through adaptive layer skipping, leveraging real-time Jacobian analysis to determine which layers to skip based on current input characteristics. By dynamically adjusting the network's depth during inference, we aim to optimize the throughput-accuracy trade-off in latency-critical environments. Our method will be grounded in PAC-Bayes theory to establish rigorous stability guarantees and bounded overhead protocols. We anticipate that this approach will not only enhance inference speed but also maintain competitive accuracy levels, significantly benefiting applications in edge computing and real-time decision-making systems. The proposed experiments will evaluate the efficacy of adaptive layer skipping in various scenarios, contrasting it with traditional static architectures.",
    "Experiments": [
