{
  "idea": {
    "Name": "adaptive_geometric_quantization",
    "Title": "Geometric Diagnostics for Adaptive Mixed-Precision Quantization",
    "Short Hypothesis": "By integrating curvature-aware geometric diagnostics into the adaptive mixed-precision quantization process, we can enhance quantization efficiency and model performance without the need for extensive training or manual tuning.",
    "Related Work": "Existing methods like EMQ and SNIP focus on training-free or adaptive approaches to mixed-precision quantization but often lack a rigorous geometric framework that quantifies stability and performance trade-offs. This proposal distinguishes itself by providing a deterministic geometric analysis that directly informs quantization decisions, thus bridging theoretical foundations with practical applications.",
    "Abstract": "In the pursuit of efficient mixed-precision quantization for deep neural networks, existing methods often rely on heuristic or training-based strategies that can be both resource-intensive and suboptimal. This proposal introduces a novel framework that integrates curvature-aware geometric diagnostics into the adaptive mixed-precision quantization process. By employing projection-based mechanistic probes, we aim to determine the optimal bit-width configurations for each layer of a neural network based on explicit numerical stability analysis and curvature metrics. This training-free approach promises to yield significant improvements in accuracy-complexity trade-offs while maintaining a deterministic execution pathway. Extensive validation will be conducted using benchmark datasets across various model architectures, ensuring generalizability and robustness. Our findings will contribute to the understanding of geometric factors in quantization, paving the way for more efficient deployment of deep learning models.",
    "Experiments": [
