    "Related Work": "Existing work, such as Isik et al. (2021), has explored the rate-distortion trade-offs in neural network compression. However, this proposal distinguishes itself by focusing specifically on deriving information-theoretic bounds on the loss of task-relevant information due to pruning, and by proposing a systematic pruning methodology that leverages these insights to optimize the compression process.",
    "Abstract": "Model compression techniques such as pruning are essential for deploying neural networks in resource-constrained environments. However, the challenge lies in balancing the compression rate with the acceptable distortion in model performance. This work investigates pruning strategies through an information-theoretic framework, treating the pruning process as a rate-distortion problem. We aim to establish theoretical bounds on the amount of task-relevant information that can be preserved while minimizing the number of parameters. By employing mutual information and description length as metrics, we will derive optimal pruning strategies that respect a given rate-distortion constraint. The proposed approach will be validated through a series of experiments on benchmark datasets, where we will measure the predictive accuracy and information retention of pruned models against theoretical limits. This research not only aims to enhance model compression techniques but also to contribute to a deeper understanding of the information-theoretic foundations of deep learning.",
