    "Title": "Dynamic Kernel Optimization for Latency-Driven Inference on GPUs",
    "Short Hypothesis": "Dynamic optimization of kernel configurations based on real-time profiling can achieve significant improvements in latency and throughput for ML inference workloads, challenging the static optimization paradigm prevalent in current frameworks.",
    "Related Work": "Prior works focus on static kernel selections or model-wise optimizations, such as KRISP and Dynamic Kernel Selection (DKS). However, they do not exploit real-time profiling data to adaptively optimize kernels during execution. This proposal introduces a novel dynamic kernel optimization approach that utilizes immediate performance metrics to adjust memory layouts and execution paths in response to workload variations, thus distinguishing itself from existing literature.",
    "Abstract": "As machine learning (ML) inference demands continue to rise, existing optimization strategies often rely on static configurations that do not adapt to real-time workload characteristics. This work proposes a dynamic kernel optimization framework that leverages real-time profiling data to adjust kernel configurations on-the-fly, enhancing latency and throughput for GPU-based inference. By instrumenting each kernel execution with performance counters, we can dynamically select memory layouts and execution paths that are best suited to the current workload, potentially leading to significant performance gains. We will evaluate our approach across various ML models, focusing on latency, throughput, and energy efficiency. Our results will provide empirical evidence of the advantages of dynamic kernel optimization, challenging traditional static optimization paradigms and paving the way for more responsive and efficient ML inference systems.",
