```json
{
  "idea": {
    "Name": "adaptive_bit_width_allocation",
    "Title": "An Information-Theoretic Framework for Adaptive Bit-Width Allocation in Mixed-Precision Quantization",
    "Short Hypothesis": "Adaptive allocation of bit-widths in mixed-precision quantization, guided by mutual information and task-specific distortion measures, can achieve superior model performance and compression trade-offs compared to existing heuristic methods.",
    "Related Work": "While recent works like SNIP and AMP-ViT focus on layer-wise importance and activation asymmetry, they primarily use heuristics for configuring precision. This proposal distinguishes itself by grounding bit-width decisions in quantifiable information-theoretic principles, allowing for a mathematically rigorous exploration of the limits of model compression and efficiency.",
    "Abstract": "In this work, we propose a novel framework for adaptive bit-width allocation in mixed-precision quantization, leveraging information-theoretic principles. By defining a direct relationship between the mutual information of model layers and their impact on task performance, we can derive achievable rates for bit allocation that minimize distortion while maximizing predictive sufficiency. Our approach will utilize empirical entropy estimates and mutual information metrics to dynamically adjust bit-widths based on the contribution of each layer to overall model accuracy. We will validate this framework through a series of experiments on standard datasets, comparing our method against state-of-the-art heuristics to demonstrate improved performance at lower computational costs. This research aims to bridge the gap between theoretical bounds and practical implementations in model compression.",
    "Experiments": [
      "1. Construct a neural network and apply standard mixed-precision quantization techniques as baselines.",
