Based on the literature search results, it is evident that there has been considerable work done on rate-distortion theory as it relates to model compression, with several studies focusing on the trade-offs between compression and generalization error, as well as the use of geometrical approaches for improving robustness in machine learning models. However, most of the existing proposals address specific implementations or applications, often linked to model performance rather than providing a theoretical foundation for understanding how different compression strategies relate to information-theoretic limits.

Given this landscape, I propose a novel research idea that aims to bridge this gap by focusing explicitly on the theoretical underpinnings of model compression through rate-distortion principles while introducing a fresh perspective on optimizing compression policies based on task relevance and representational efficiency.

