    "Abstract": "This research proposes a novel framework for adaptive compression policies in neural networks, grounded in rate-distortion theory. We hypothesize that dynamic adjustments to compression rates, driven by real-time evaluations of task-relevant distortion metrics, can enhance model performance and generalization. By framing compression as a rate-distortion optimization problem, we will derive a formal methodology that quantifies the trade-off between compression rate and predictive accuracy. Our approach will leverage mutual information measures to allocate bits efficiently across model parameters, ensuring that the most critical weights are preserved in lower precision while less essential weights are aggressively compressed. Through a series of experiments, we will validate our hypothesis by observing improvements in predictive sufficiency in various tasks, including image classification and natural language processing. The ultimate goal is to establish a theoretical framework that connects bit allocation strategies with operational limits, providing a clearer understanding of the relationship between information theory and model compression.",
    "Experiments": [
      "Implement a baseline model with static compression rates across all layers.",
      "Develop an adaptive compression mechanism that adjusts rates based on real-time task-relevant distortion metrics derived from the model's output.",
