{
  "idea": {
    "Name": "dynamic_mixed_precision_kernel",
    "Title": "Dynamic Mixed-Precision Kernel Optimization for Hardware-Focused Inference of Large Language Models",
    "Short Hypothesis": "Dynamic adjustment of mixed-precision quantization levels based on real-time GPU profiling can significantly enhance inference throughput and reduce latency in large language models without sacrificing accuracy.",
    "Related Work": "While existing frameworks like SNIP and KVTuner focus on layer-wise quantization sensitivity and optimization, they do not fully exploit dynamic profiling to optimize mixed-precision inference in real-time on commodity hardware. Our approach distinguishes itself by emphasizing on-device profiling and real-time adjustments, ensuring the proposed quantization strategy is hardware-specific and empirically validated.",
    "Abstract": "Large language models (LLMs) have achieved remarkable performance across a variety of tasks, yet their deployment remains constrained by high computational demands. Existing mixed-precision quantization methods often rely on static configurations that do not consider the dynamic nature of GPU performance. In this proposal, we introduce a novel dynamic mixed-precision kernel that adapts quantization levels based on real-time profiling metrics obtained through GPU instrumentation. By leveraging performance feedback, including occupancy, memory bandwidth, and kernel execution time, the proposed kernel dynamically adjusts the precision of computations to maximize throughput while adhering to accuracy constraints. We will evaluate the effectiveness of this approach through comprehensive profiling and benchmarking on multiple commodity GPUs, focusing on wall-clock latency, tokens-per-second, and energy consumption. Our goal is to provide an empirical foundation for mixed-precision optimization that can be readily implemented in production environments, ultimately enhancing the deployment of LLMs in resource-constrained scenarios.",
    "Experiments": [
