    "Title": "Empirical Mixed-Precision Quantization: A Hardware-First Approach to Optimize Inference Performance",
    "Short Hypothesis": "By employing an empirical profiling strategy to determine optimal bit-widths per layer of deep learning models, we can achieve significant performance improvements in inference speed and efficiency on commodity GPUs without the need for complex automated frameworks.",
    "Related Work": "While existing research such as HAQ and SNIP utilize complex algorithms for hardware-aware quantization, they often require extensive training and do not focus solely on direct empirical measurements from hardware. This proposal distinctly emphasizes a hands-on, profiling-driven methodology that ties quantization decisions directly to measured performance metrics, thereby simplifying the process and making it more practical for immediate deployment.",
    "Abstract": "In this proposal, we introduce an empirical approach to mixed-precision quantization that prioritizes hardware performance metrics over complex algorithmic frameworks. By systematically profiling deep learning models on commodity GPUs, we aim to determine the optimal bit-width for each layer based on direct measurements of latency, throughput, and energy consumption. This method contrasts with existing approaches that often rely on automated tuning or theoretical frameworks. Our experiments will focus on collecting detailed performance data through profiling tools, enabling us to establish a clear correlation between quantization strategies and real-world hardware performance. We will evaluate the proposed approach on various models and datasets, aiming to provide reproducible benchmarks that can be implemented in real-time applications.",
