    "Short Hypothesis": "Integrating rate-distortion optimization directly into the quantization process can significantly enhance the performance of compressed neural networks by systematically allocating bits based on task-relevant information.",
    "Related Work": "Current methods like SNIP and AMP-ViT focus on mixed precision and adaptive quantization with heuristic approaches. However, they lack a robust theoretical framework based on rate-distortion principles that quantifies the trade-offs and provides guarantees on information retention under various compression regimes.",
    "Abstract": "As the size of deep learning models continues to grow, efficient compression techniques are essential for deployment on resource-constrained devices. This proposal introduces a novel framework that integrates rate-distortion optimization into the quantization process for neural networks, systematically allocating bits in accordance with task-relevant information while minimizing distortion. By utilizing principles from coding theory, we will derive a quantization scheme that aligns with the fundamental limits of model compression, yielding an efficient trade-off between model size and predictive accuracy. We will evaluate this approach against standard benchmarks and compare it to existing methods like SNIP and AMP-ViT, demonstrating its advantages in preserving crucial model characteristics while achieving significant reductions in memory and computational requirements. Our proposed method aims to set a new standard in model compression that is both theoretically grounded and empirically validated.",
    "Experiments": [
      "1. Quantization Framework Development: Implement a quantization algorithm based on rate-distortion optimization principles, allowing for flexibility in bit allocation across layers based on calculated mutual information.",
      "2. Benchmarking: Compare the performance of the proposed quantization framework against existing methods (such as SNIP and AMP-ViT) using established datasets like ImageNet and CIFAR-10.",
      "3. Evaluation Metrics: Assess model performance through accuracy, compression rate (bits-per-weight), and distortion metrics (e.g., mean squared error), analyzing the relationship between quantization levels and task performance.",
