    "Short Hypothesis": "By leveraging mutual information as a guide for adaptive quantization, we can optimally allocate bit-widths in neural networks to minimize task-relevant distortion while adhering to a specified rate constraint.",
    "Related Work": "Existing works, such as 'Rate Distortion For Model Compression' (Gao et al., 2018) and 'Radio: Rate-Distortion Optimization for Large Language Model Compression' (Young, 2025), have explored the theoretical foundations of rate-distortion in model compression but have not sufficiently addressed how to dynamically adapt quantization levels based on mutual information metrics. Our approach distinguishes itself by integrating task-relevant distortion measures more directly into the quantization decision process.",
    "Abstract": "In this proposal, we introduce a novel framework for adaptive quantization of neural networks that is driven by mutual information between model parameters and task outputs. By applying rate-distortion theory, we aim to develop a quantization strategy that dynamically adjusts bit-widths for each layer based on their contribution to overall task performance. This approach will involve defining a task-specific distortion measure and utilizing mutual information to guide the adaptive allocation of precision. We hypothesize that this method will not only achieve better model performance at lower bit-costs but also provide theoretical insights into the fundamental limits of model compression. The proposed experiments will validate the effectiveness of this adaptive quantization strategy against state-of-the-art methods.",
    "Experiments": [
      "Define a set of neural network architectures across different domains (e.g., vision, language).",
      "Implement a baseline quantization method using fixed bit-widths for comparison.",
