To refine and improve my initial proposal, I will focus on a novel approach that aims to bridge the gap between theoretical limits and practical applications by introducing a new method of quantization based on an information-theoretic perspective. This method will seek to provide a provable framework for quantization that can adaptively allocate bits based on the task's complexity and the model's structure.

### Refined Proposal

IDEA JSON:
```json
{
  "idea": {
    "Name": "adaptive_information_theoretic_quantization",
    "Title": "Adaptive Information-Theoretic Quantization for Model Compression",
    "Short Hypothesis": "By framing quantization as a rate-distortion problem, we can develop an adaptive quantization scheme that allocates bits to parameters based on their contribution to task-relevant information, leading to improved model compression without sacrificing performance.",
    "Related Work": "While rate-distortion theory has been applied to model compression (Gao et al., 2018; Isik et al., 2021; Young, 2025), existing methods often lack a clear adaptive mechanism for bit allocation. Our proposal distinguishes itself by introducing a framework that dynamically adjusts the bit-width for each parameter based on its mutual information with the task, which has not been thoroughly explored in the literature.",
    "Abstract": "Model compression is critical for deploying deep learning models in resource-constrained environments. Current quantization techniques often apply fixed bit-widths across parameters, leading to suboptimal performance and inefficiencies. In this proposal, we introduce an adaptive quantization framework grounded in rate-distortion theory, allowing for dynamic bit allocation based on the task-relevant information of each model parameter. We will derive theoretical guarantees for the proposed method and validate it through experiments on various neural network architectures. Our results will provide insights into the relationship between quantization, model performance, and information preservation, paving the way for more efficient model compression techniques.",
    "Experiments": [
      "1. Implement the proposed adaptive quantization method on a set of benchmark neural networks (e.g., ResNet, ViT) and compare it against fixed bit-width quantization methods.",
