Arguments: {"idea": {"Name": "dynamic_kernel_fusion", "Title": "Dynamic Kernel Fusion: Optimizing Memory Bandwidth and Latency in GPU Inference", "Short Hypothesis": "This research proposes a novel dynamic kernel fusion strategy that adapts to varying memory bandwidth demands during inference, aiming to improve wall-clock latency without compromising accuracy across dynamic deep learning models. Existing frameworks often rely on static optimization strategies that fail to account for real-time variations in workload, leading to suboptimal performance.", "Related Work": "While existing works like NeuSight focus on predicting performance and frameworks like Grape address dynamic executions, they do not fully utilize dynamic kernel fusion based on real-time profiling metrics. Our approach explicitly integrates runtime memory bandwidth monitoring to adaptively fuse kernels on-the-fly, which is distinct from prior work that relies on pre-compiled optimization strategies.", "Abstract": "Modern deep learning models often exhibit dynamic behavior, with varying input sizes and control flows that challenge static optimization techniques. This proposal introduces Dynamic Kernel Fusion (DKF), a framework that leverages real-time profiling of memory bandwidth and compute demands to adaptively fuse CUDA kernels for inference on GPUs. By monitoring memory usage and latency during execution, DKF can dynamically adjust the fusion strategy to minimize data transfers and maximize throughput, achieving optimized wall-clock latency across a variety of workloads. We will implement DKF within an existing inference engine and evaluate its performance against static kernel fusion techniques, measuring improvements in p50/p99 latency, throughput under batching, and energy consumption per token. We believe that this approach not only enhances the efficiency of dynamic DNNs but also provides a reproducible method for hardware-aware optimizations that can be deployed in practical environments.", "Experiments": "1. Implement DKF in a CUDA-based inference engine. 2. Profile memory bandwidth and latency while running dynamic DNNs (e.g., GPT variants, Wav2Vec2). 3. Compare DKF against static kernel fusion techniques by measuring p50/p99 latency and throughput for varying input sizes. 4. Conduct A/B tests to assess the effect of dynamic fusion on energy consumption per token.", "Risk Factors and Limitations": "The primary risk is the potential overhead of real-time profiling affecting performance gains. Additionally, the complexity of dynamically managing kernel fusion may introduce challenges in maintaining accuracy across different models. Finally, the approach may require extensive integration with existing frameworks, which could limit immediate applicability."}}
