### Reflection on the Initial Proposal
The initial proposal I was considering was centered around leveraging rate-distortion theory to investigate the compressibility of deep learning models through a novel quantization scheme. It aimed to derive theoretical bounds on the bits-per-weight needed for predictive sufficiency while also providing practical methods to achieve these bounds. 

**Quality and Novelty**: The proposal is of high quality and aligns well with current trends in understanding model efficiency. However, it can be further refined to address specific gaps in the literature regarding dynamic model compression.

**Feasibility**: The proposed experiments are feasible within an academic lab setting, focusing on theoretical derivations and simulations rather than heavy empirical testing with extensive resources.

**Clarification of Distinction**: The original idea could benefit from clearer differentiation from existing works, particularly those focused on static quantization strategies like SQR and others mentioned.

### Refined Proposal

I will refine the proposal to emphasize dynamic quantization strategies based on real-time information-theoretic analysis of model performance and predictive sufficiency.

