    "Related Work": "While previous works have explored static quantization techniques and their performance bounds, they often overlook how dynamic adjustments based on real-time activation statistics can optimize model compression. Notably, works like SQR focus on static precision allocation, lacking a framework that dynamically adapts quantization levels based on information-theoretic metrics.",
    "Abstract": "This proposal investigates a novel approach to model compression through dynamic quantization, framed within an information-theoretic context. By leveraging real-time assessment of model activations and their associated predictive sufficiency, we aim to develop a framework that allocates quantization levels dynamically. Our hypothesis posits that such an adaptive scheme can reduce distortion while maintaining performance metrics, thus enabling more efficient model deployment. We will derive theoretical bounds on bits-per-weight for various model architectures and establish a distortion-rate curve that reflects the achievable compression rates. Empirical evaluations will compare our dynamic quantization method against static baselines, emphasizing the benefits of adaptability in quantization during inference. This work aims to contribute to the understanding of how information-theoretic principles can enhance model compression strategies.",
