    "Short Hypothesis": "Adaptive quantization of model weights based on local entropy estimates can achieve near-optimal compression rates while minimizing distortion, providing a dynamic framework for model efficiency that outperforms static quantization approaches.",
    "Related Work": "Recent advances in model compression have explored static quantization strategies and training-free methods based on activation geometry. However, these methods often fail to dynamically adjust to the varying distribution of model parameters during inference. Our approach distinguishes itself by leveraging local entropy estimates to inform adaptive quantization, thereby addressing the limitations of existing static methods and enhancing compression efficiency.",
    "Abstract": "In the quest for efficient model compression, we propose a novel adaptive quantization framework that utilizes localized entropy estimates of model weight distributions to inform quantization strategies. This approach is grounded in information-theoretic principles, framing the compression of model parameters as a rate-distortion problem. By dynamically adjusting the quantization levels based on the entropy of weight distributions encountered during inference, we aim to minimize the distortion in task performance while achieving optimal bit allocation. Our experiments will validate this hypothesis against established static quantization methods, measuring the trade-offs between compression rates and predictive performance. We anticipate that our method will yield significant improvements in both compression efficiency and model robustness, establishing a new frontier in adaptive model compression.",
    "Experiments": [
